{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_jennings_ver01/data/sn95047246/00529042218/1930091801/0420.xml":{"full_text":"Thursday, September 18. 1930\nTHE BROOKSVILLE JOURNAL\nPUBLISHED BY\nThe Russell Publishing Co.\nBROOKSVILLE, FLORIDA\nE. R. RUSSELL. EDITOR AND BUSINESS MANAGER\nTAYLOR DAWSON, CITY EDITOR\nPublished Every Thursday\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES:\nSix Months 1-00\nThree Months 45\nOne Year 2OO\nEntered at the Postoffice in Brooksville, Florida, as matter of the second\nclass.\nSTATE SALARIES.\nFor the past several months much has been said regarding\nthe salaries of state and county officials in an endeavor to work\nout the problems of lower taxation. Little can be done at this\ntime in the reduction of taxes because of the vast bond issues\nnow voted upon the several counties of the state. The salaries\nof officials count for much but it remains a small item when it\nconies to counting up the principal and interest of bond issues.\nHigh taxation comes with enormous bond issues and not especi\nally from the salaries paid state and county officials.\nThe Journal claims, however, that every little bit helps and\nwith the cutting of salaries of officials, the burden of taxation\ncan be made some easier.\nFor the information of the readers of the Journal, we print\nherewith the salaries of state officials as they are today:\nGovernor, $10,000; Secretary to Governor. $6,000; State\nComptroller. $6,000; Bank Report Analyst, $4,500 Attorney\nGeneral. $6,000: two assistants, $5,000 each; State Treasurer,\n$6,000; Commissioner of Agriculture, $6,000; State Shellfish\nCommissioner, $5.000: Superintendent Public Instruction,\n$6,000; Six Supreme Court Justices, $9,600 each; 39 Circuit\nJudges. $7,500 each; Four States Attorneys, $7,500 each; Two\nStates Attorneys. $5,000 eadv Five States Attorneys, $4,200\neach; State Geologist. $4,000; State Chemist, S 4.000; Commis\nsioner State Marketing Bureau. $5,000; State Auditor, $4,500;\nState Tax Equalizer. $4,000; three Railroad Commissioners,\n$5,000 each: General Counsel. $6,000; Rate Expert, $4,200\nTelephone Engineer. $4,000; Accountant. $4,200; Game and\nFreshwater Commissioner. $5,000; Hotel Commissioner, $5,-\n(100; Motor Vehicle Commissioner. $5,000; Chairman State\nRoad Department. $7,500; Attorney. $4,200; Highway Engi\nneer, $6,000; Assistant Engineer. $5.000 Bridge Engineer.\n$4,200; Division Engineers. $4,200 each; State Health Officer.\n$5,000; State Veterinarian. $4,500; Commissioner of Public\nWelfare. $4,000; State Forester, $4,200; Adjutant General.\n$5,000; Superintendent Florida State Hospital, $6,000; Super\nintendent State Prison Farm. $4,500; President School Deaf\nand Blind. $4.000 President A. M. College for Negroes. $4.-\n500; Assistant Director Experiment Stations, $4,200; Horti\nculturist. $4,500; Agronomist. $4,000; Associate Animal Hus\nbandry, $4,500; Chemist, $4,400; Entomologist. $4,000; Plant\nPathologist. $4,800; Associate. $4,000; Tobacco Plant Pathol\nogist. $4,500; Soils Specialist. Everglades Section, $4,800\u2022\nNursery Inspector. $4,000; Quarantine Itiifpector, $4,380.\nCONSTRUCTION IN THE SOUTH.\nFor eight months ending August, construction contracts in\nthe South aggregated more than $702,000,000, a record\namount. Also, a new high construction record was set by the\nsouth during the past three summer months of June, July and\nAugust. Contracts awarded for that period compiled from re\nports <>f projects with a valuation of more than $lO,OOO each, as\npublished in the Daily Construction Bulletin, amounted in the\naggregate to more than $390,000,000. This three months\u2019 to-1\ntai was 543.000.000 higher than the previous summer record;\nmade during the corresponding months of 1928, and in excess:\nof the total for the first six months of 1925 and 1927.\nThe Manufacturers' Record thus tells of what the nation is\ndoing along this line.\nOne billion, live hundred million dollars, a part of it appro\npriated by congress and a part provided by a few leading private\nindustries, is on deposit, as it were, ready for payment on con\nstruction work. With carry-overs of unfinished work from\nlast year, the grant total may be estimated at $2,000,000,000.\n\"Of far more weight than its value in mere dollars, how\never, is the fact that this sum may be regarded as a sound and\npractical inspiration for active employment of other millions or\neven billions in all lines of American industry, with consequent\nrelief for unemployment and the promotion of normal Ameri\ncan prosperity. This fund may well be pictured as a means of\nstarting men and machinery to work, in profitable production\nand at liberal pay. in every part of the country.\n\"The fact that this $1,500,000,000 is only ,a drop' in the\nreservoir of American dollar.- available for business revival ap\npears in the disclosure that it comes only from a half dozen\nsources.\"\u2014Tallahassee Democrat.\nIf the editors of certain papers scattered over the state who\nare habitually \"roasting\" Governor Carlton solely because lie\nbested their champion in the political arena, would forget past\npolitics and co-operate with the administration in all construc\ntive efforts, a decided step would be taken in the movement to\nmake conditions lietter in all sections of Florida.\u2014Palatka Her\nald. Disgruntled politicians and habitual knockers count for\nmuch in Florida today. They are doing the state a great harm\nand Florida voters should remember this when the next election\nrolls around. Many of these politicians will be up for \u201csome\nthing\" and it would be well for the people to take due notice of\nwhat is happening today.\nFrom reports coming to the Journal the cows are now run\nning at large throughout the city and disturbing the flower gar\ndens and shrubbery, and otherwise doing great damage. It ap\npears now about the time to take the matter in hand as local\nresidents are desirous of putting out new plants and improving\ntheir premises. Mr. Councilman and Mr. Policeman, what can\nbe done about it?\nHardee's candidacy for governor is gaining momentum ac\ncording to the state press. By 1932 may be the former gover\nnor will have a large enough following to insure his election.\nSheriff Cobb warns \u201csling-shot\u201d shooters. Young man. if\nyou own one of these \u201cthings,\u201d you had better get rid of it.\nThe sheriff means business and he will not be \"tinkered with.\u201d\nMuch harm has been done in the past by the use of these sling\nshots and it is high time they should be done away with. See\nthe sheriff's notice in this issue of the Journal.\n\u201cPlant a garden\u201d is a good slogan. In this day of unrest\na good garden counts for much. Turn that back yard into\nsomething worth while. It will pay you.\n\u201cPound\u201d the cows and beautify your premises\nNOBLETON\nBETTIE W. OWEN\nFrank Sanchez was an early\nmorning visitor, on Wednesday.\nMiss Mary Sarver made a call on\nMrs. G. W. Owen on Thursday\nevening.\nMr. John Le\u00dfoy, of Brooksville,\ncalled at the home of Mrs. G. W.\nOwen, on Thursday afternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. Harry Miller, of\nAlliance, Ohio, have just, at this\nwriting, arrived for another Flor\nida winter.\nHarrison Kitchen, of Brooksville,\nwas a visitor in town, on Thurs\nday. in the interests of the Florida\nPower Corporation.\nMrs. F. A. Hawley, who has\nbeen visiting relatives, here, for the\npast two weeks, returned to her\nhome, in Orlando, on Sunday.\nMrs. Wm. Beckholt and her\nhouse guest, Mrs. Fanny A. Haw\nley, called on their friend and\nneighbor, Mrs. G. W. Owen, on\nThursday afternoon.\nMiss Mary Sarver and Mrs.\nEverett Shardein left on Friday\nfor Tampa, from which place the\nlatter expects to leave for Louis\nville, Kentucky.\nMr. and Mrs. Harr}- Powell en\ntertained Mr. and Mrs. James Dew\nberry, of Camp Carrick, at dinner\non Wednesday evening, in honor\nof Mrs. Dewberry's birthday.\nThe residents of this section are\nall sorry that Mr. Carn will no\nlonger call to deliver the ice; the\nCarns having sold out their interest\nin the ice plant. The ice will be\ndelivered as usual but Mr. Carn\nwill be much missed, as he was so\nwell liked by all.\nOne of our people has received\na letter from Mr. Chas. Hamilton,\nof Boston. Massachusetts, saying\nthat he and his family expect to be\nwith us. again, for the coming win\nter and are planning to make an\nearly start.\nThe members of the Lake Lind\nsey B. Y. P. U. gave a \u2018Pie party'\non Friday evening. This unique\nparty was held at the home of Mrs.\nCarrie Baxley and a full quota of\nthe members and their friends were\npresent, all enjoying a remarkably\ngood time.\nHurrah! The first of our regular\nwinter residents arrived on Friday\nmorning when Mr. and Mrs. Frank\nPeckham, of Rochester, New York,\ndrove up to their Nobleton home.\nThey having motored down with\nfriends, who were bound for Mia\nmi. We were all delighted to wel\ncome \"Uncle Frank\" and \u201cAunt\nAbbie.\"\nHAPPYDAY FARM Milk is truly a\nbottle of sunshine for your child.\nRichest in all vitamines, both the bone\nbuilding mineral ones, and in the cream,\nVitamines \u201cA\u201d and \u201cD\u201d, strongest in heat\nvalue.\nGIVE it to the youngsters at meal\ntimes and after school. Bottled\nin our sanitary dairy, Happyday Farm\nmilk is the most healthful and economical\nfood.\nRICHEST IN VITAMINES\nHappyday Farm\nPHONE 130\nBROOKSVILLE, FLA.\nTHE BROOKSVILLE JOURNAL\nMr. and Mrs. D. L. Hawley of\nOrlando, Miss Martha Hawley of\nTitusville, and Miss Irma Thomp\nson, of Mulberry were guests, on\nSunday, at the home of Mr. and\nMrs. Wm. Beckholt.\nMrs. James Haywood entertain\ned, on Friday, in honor of her sis-1\nter, who is here from her home in\nEllenton and is visiting with her.\nThose present were Mrs. Stevens,\nMr. Smith. Mrs. Ida Higginboth\nam. Mrs. Ella Sellers, of Ocala.\nMr. J. C. Graham. Mrs. Bessie Dib\nble. Miss Yilas Williams, Mrs. G.\nW. Owen, David Townsend. Ken\nneth Townsend. Mrs. Mary Young,\nthe honoree, and Mrs. Dora Town\nsend, the hostess.\nMIDNIGHT REVERIES\nWhile, restless, I tossed upon my\nbed.\nEre sleep would come to me.\nSome scenes of far-dimmed visions,\nI seemed to, plainly, see.\nScenes, which with daybreak\u2019s\ndawning.\nSeemed to take swift wings and\nflee.\nFor the many hours of daytime.\nSo filled with strife and care;\nSeemed to find no place to harbor\nSuch thoughts; so sweet and fair.\nWhich rise, like champagne bub\nbles,\nOn a vintage, rich and rare.\nThese restless hours of midnight,\nSeem a blessing in disguise,\n\"Tis then that thoughts arise,\nWhile the hours drag drear and\nlong,\nWith the heart's best ones that lin\nger.\nLike a half-forgotten, deep-hid\nsong.\nO. these night-forgotten visions;\nThey fill with thoughts that still\nwill please,\nAnd they' play upon our heart\nstrings,\nAs they waft down Memory\u2019s\nbreeze.\nSo, I say\u2019, such hours are surely\nblest,\nEven if we do miss a bit of rest.\n\u2014Bettie W. Owen,\nNobleton, Florida.\nMarried Woman\nFears Gas \u2014Eats\nOnly Baby Food\n\"For 3 years I ate only baby food,;\neverything else formed gas. Now,'\nI thanks to Adlerika. I eat anything!\nand enjoy life.\"\u2014Mrs. M. Gunn.\nJust ONE spoonful Adlerika re-1\nlieves all GAS so you can cat and\nc sleep better. Acts on BOTH upper\nand lower bowel removing poisons\nyou never knew were there, and\ni which caused your stomach trouble.\nNo matter what you have tried for\nstomach and bowels, Adlerika will\nt surprise you! Murphy\u2019s Drug\nStore. adv\nAMERICA LEADS\nIN CHEMICALS\nThe United States is the largest\nsingle factor in the World\u2019s chemi\ncal industry and one-half of the\nfive-billion dollar output of chemi\ncals is claimed for our Nation.\nIt is well known that Germany\nwas the \u201cwhite-haired\" leader in\nmany branches of the chemical in\ndustry, notably dyes, before the\nwar, but that nation lost a good\ndeal of its supremacy to America.\nAccording to the Commerce De\npartment industrial chemicals are\nsold largely to manufacturers for\nspecial uses in other products. It\nis these products that are advertis\ned and not the raw materials which\nhave been chemically treated by the\nchemical industry.\nChildren Almost Hate\nCross, Nervous Mother\n\u201cMy children almost hated me. I\nwas so cross. Thanks to X inol, my\nnervousness is all gone and we are\nhappy again.\"\u2014Mrs. T. Johnstone.\nFor 30 years doctors have pre\nscribed Vinol because it contains\nimportant mineral elements of iron,\ncalcium and cod liver peptone. The\nvery FIRST bottle brings sound\nsleep and a BIG appetite. Nervous,\nwornout people are surprised how\nQUICK Vinol gives new life and\npep! Tastes delicious. V. V.\nCooglcr, Druggist. adv\nStill Good!\nHEELS run down? Soles\nthrough? Ripped?\nPshaw, that\u2019s nothing. Just\nlet us get our hands on those\nshoes and we'll prove that\nthey\u2019re good for many\nmoons more. Our expert\nrepairing and polishing\nservice cuts sss and sss\nfrom your footwear budget.\nMARTIN MALECKA\nSHOE SHOP\n9 So. Main St.\nBrooksville. Florida\nDr. F. E. McClane\nWILL BE IN\nBROOKSVILLE, FLORIDA\nONE DAY ONLY\nSaturday, Oct. 11th\nTemporary Office\nTangerine Hotel\nWhere he will be pleased to\nmeet any of his old patients, and\nany' one else who would desire\nto consult with him, in regard\nto any physical disability.\nDoctor McClane\nrepresents\nThe McClane\nHealth Institute\nST. PETERSBURG, FLA.\nThe most elaborate and best\nequipped institution in the south,\nfor the treatment of old obscure,\nand long standing disabilities,\netc. Rectal troubles, Piles. Fis\ntulas, etc., can be cured without\nusing the knife.\nSatisfaction Guaranteed\nCancer and abdominal growths\ntreated scientifically, and with\ngreat success.\nThe is your opportunity to con\nsult the doctor in regard to your\ndisability.\nREMEMBER THE DATE\nSaturday, Oct. 11th\nOffice Hours, 8 A. M. to 6 P. M.\nTangerine Hotel\nBROOKSVILLE, FLORIDA\nWRITE FOR LITERATURE\nAND INFORMATION\nMake Your Appointment Early\nInquire about BOR-JEC reme\ndies for Home Treatment.\nLONGER j\nB kM WEAR I\nmore\nNON-SKID\nTHICKER, I\ntread\nWill y7OU\u2019VE wondered hoW\nFireston* eould build\nbetter tire*. But here they j\nare more tread mb* 1\nber with 25% more non\nskid life and 36% more\n11* wear\u2014think of it I Deeper,\nquicker action tread\u2014more\ncontact with the road\u2014\u2022\nmore rubber between the\nplies. Stronger, tougher,\nsafer tires than ever be*\nfore. Equip your ear with\n,et today and ride on tha\ngreatest tires ever made,\nI \u00abIJM* DIPPED\n-Km u.i uuiMti Ji i. mu it\nAMSTUTZ MOTOR COMPANY\nBrooksville, Fla. Phone 17j5\nMaillis Grocery Co.\n\u201cThe Home Merchant\u201d \u201cThe Independent Grocer\u201d\n\"WHEN YOU WANT SOMETHING QUICK\"\nPHONE 9\nWE DELIVER WITHIN THE CITY LIMITS\nPRICES FOR SATURDAY ONLY.\n(10 Lb. Limit) 5 Lbs. 10 Lbs.\nSUGAR 25c 50c\nGolden Key or Every Day 3 Tall or 6 Small\nMILK 25c\nIRISH\nPOTATOES 10 lbs. 39c\nMorning Jov Lb.\nCOFFEE 45c\nPER LB.\n^Coffee 39c\nWhiteway or Roadway Per Lb.\nCOFFEE 23c\nArmour\u2019s Veri-Best Grape 16 Oz. Glass\nJELLY 25c\nGold Bar or Oversea No 2 1-2\nPEACHES 25c\n(Regular 35c Value)\nGold Bar No 2 1-2 Can\nPEACHES 25c\nEagle Brand 24 Lb. Sack\nFLOUR 79c\nRockford\u2019s \u201cPure\u201d 1-2 Lb\nCOCOA 10c\n2 Lbs.\nLARD 25c\nBrooksville 3 p or\nBREAD 25c\n\"TbarTfor\nTOILET SOAP 20c\net beautiful greten glass cup and saucer free. See them today\nbefore the are all gone)","height":"20476","width":"14668"}}
